<section class="section bio-human">
  <div class="bio-layout">
    <div class="bio-main">
      <p class="bio-intro">
        If you had told me a decade ago, while I was finishing my <strong>Ph.D. in Law</strong>, that I would spend my days measuring leaves and discussing seedling viability in forests, I wouldn't have believed you.
      </p>

      <p>
        My transition from legal scholarship to founding <strong>Petiole</strong> wasn't just a career change; it was a response to a "brutal truth." I saw a gap where technology was too complex for the people who actually needed it. My legal training taught me how systems are built, but my life as a founder taught me how they are broken—and fixed.
      </p>

      <div class="truth-box">
        <h3>The "Before Sunrise" Mindset</h3>
        <p>
          Moving from a small town in Ukraine to Heathrow Airport with a UK Global Talent Visa wasn't about luck. It was about waking up before the sun to bridge the distance between where I was and where I needed to be. I bring that same relentless energy to every policy briefing and every line of computer vision code we develop.
        </p>
      </div>

      <p>
        Today, my work sits at the intersection of three worlds: <strong>the precision of AI</strong>, <strong>the rigor of policy</strong>, and <strong>the reality of the field</strong>. Whether I’m advising the World Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO) or working with fellow innovators at the Oxford Farming Conference, my goal is the same: to make technology feel human and innovation feel inevitable.
      </p>
    </div>

